  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2523319012" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2523319012" />
    <a title="Joseph Stieb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5862443-joseph-stieb"><img alt="Joseph Stieb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614110248p2/5862443.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2523319012?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joseph Stieb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joseph Stieb" href="/user/show/5862443-joseph-stieb">Joseph Stieb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5862443-joseph-stieb?shelf=us-history-non-military">us-history-non-military</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2523319012" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16959799489687621413">A hefty listen that was compelling in many ways but frustrating as a book. Let&apos;s start with the downsides. This book is very much an account of the day to day running and strategy of the SCLC, with an intense focus on administration and deliberation. This isn&apos;t always uninteresting, especially when you see how they worked through different problems and challenges. However, if you are looking for a deep dive into the ideas or cultural influences behind the Civil Rights movement (CRM), then this i</span>
  <span id="freeText16959799489687621413" style="display:none">A hefty listen that was compelling in many ways but frustrating as a book. Let's start with the downsides. This book is very much an account of the day to day running and strategy of the SCLC, with an intense focus on administration and deliberation. This isn't always uninteresting, especially when you see how they worked through different problems and challenges. However, if you are looking for a deep dive into the ideas or cultural influences behind the Civil Rights movement (CRM), then this isn't the book. Garrow only gives snapshots of that, making his book more of a chronicle than a thesis-driven book.<br /><br />This criticism aside, I learned a lot from this book, and I was struck by certain aspects of King and the CRM. The first is the sheer exhaustion that beset King from his endless, enervating schedule of rallies, speeches, fund-raising, writing, administrating, and service as a pastor. Garrow creates a vivid sense of how King never really escaped the movement, and how he often became dejected and depressed. <br /><br />The book also provides an interesting account of the rivalries between major CR groups like the SCLC, SNCC, CORE, the NAACP, and the Urban League. This is quite a tawdry history, and SNCC and the NAACP leadership comes off pretty badly. Moreover, you can see the radicalization of King and the CRM take place over time, even though Garrow doesn't offer a thesis on why this happened. Still, it is undeniable that King post 65 was far less optimistic about appealing to the consciences of white Americans and convincing them to help with this change. he came to see the US in almost Malcolm X-ian terms: scarred on a fundamental level by the sin of racism and in need of fundamental reforms (socialism, essentially, for King) rather than just a seat at the table for AA's.<br /><br />This was a tragic development because King had just achieved 2 major victories in 1964 and 1965. Yet, there was a certain reasonableness or inevitability to this shift in King, which paralleled the radicalization of the CRM. The Civil Rights and Voting Rights Act were huge accomplishments, but they were just the start of the black quest for true equality and power. Garrow's excellent account of the SCLC's struggle for fair housing and employment in Chicago really brought this point to the fore. Without an openly racist city leadership like there was in Selma or Birmingham, it was harder to dramatize the situation and attract national media attention. Jim Crow segregation was openly violent, ugly in its racism, and stark in its discrimination. Prejudice and discrimination were rife in a divided city like Chicago, but harder to bring to the fore, more embedded in economic and demographic/geographic forces than in the snarling face of Bull Connor and his German shepherds. The white question "What do they want now?" haunted the post 1965 CRM, and sympathy clearly declined if not completely reversed as racial backlash politics gained strength from the mid 60s to the 70s.<br /><br />So the King story is not only a tragedy because of his early death but because the frustration he felt in the years before his death signaled where America was going on race: a strange dual track of colorblindness, in which ongoing and systematic inequality and discrimination in wealth, housing, education, criminal justice, etc could be explained away by a nation that no longer wanted to face up to these problems or the enduring significance of race. One of the many great achievements of King was that he got the nation to do this at all, even if it was just for a brief window. That's the enduring contradiction of the civil rights movement.<br /><br />Because this book is freakin long and not very analytical, I wouldn't recommend it unless you are teaching the CRM and just need a blow by blow account. It is a monumental achievement in research and organization, but it leaves the mind grasping for a deeper understanding of trends, forces, and ideas.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16959799489687621413" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

